│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in                            │
│ BoUpSLP::ShuffleCostEstimator::computeExtractCost() due to an assertion  │
│ failure: (Idx + EltsPerVector) <= BaseVF. This happens when estimating   │
│ the cost of extracting a subvector from a larger base vector. The        │
│ computed starting index Idx for the subvector extract can exceed the     │
│ valid range, leading to the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\nThe │
│ logs show that the SLP vectorizer successfully vectorizes several        │
│ store/xor/load chains. The crash happens later when attempting to        │
│ analyze a small extract sequence during horizontal reduction             │
│ processing:\n- It tries to vectorize bundles like %1 = extractelement <4 │
│ x i32> %0, i32 0 and %9 = extractelement <4 x i32> %8, i32 1.\n- In      │
│ computeExtractCost, NumElts is determined by the source vectors (4       │
│ here). EltsPerVector is the per-part element count (2 for VL size=2,     │
│ NumParts=1). The helper CheckPerRegistersShuffle returns shuffle kinds   │
│ and Indices where subvector extracts are required.\n- The assertion      │
│ fires because an Index value can be equal to NumElts (e.g., OffsetReg0=4 │
│ aligned down to 4), so Idx + EltsPerVector = 4 + 2 = 6 > BaseVF (which   │
│ is typically 4 here), violating the bound.\n\n3. Root Cause              │
│ Analysis:\nIn CheckPerRegistersShuffle, we initialize Indices with       │
│ OffsetReg0:\n  Indices.assign(1, OffsetReg0);\nLater, for the second     │
│ register, we push back OffsetReg1 % NumElts. However, the first index    │
│ (OffsetReg0) is not reduced modulo NumElts. If Mask indicates elements   │
│ that start from an index equal to or beyond NumElts (due to concatenated │
│ register view), OffsetReg0 can be >= NumElts. When computeExtractCost    │
│ then uses this Idx to estimate SK_ExtractSubvector cost with BaseVF      │
│ derived from alignTo(NumElts, EltsPerVector), Idx + EltsPerVector can    │
│ exceed BaseVF, triggering the assertion.\nTherefore, the bug is that the │
│ first index is not normalized to the subvector base range, unlike the    │
│ second index. This mismatch can produce out-of-range subvector extract   │
│ indices.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- Edit Point (lines 12105-12106  │
│ in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp):\n  Change the       │
│ initialization of Indices so that the first index is normalized,         │
│ consistent with the second index. Replace:\n    Indices.assign(1,        │
│ OffsetReg0);\n  with:\n    Indices.assign(1, OffsetReg0 %                │
│ NumElts);\n\nReasoning:\n- This ensures both indices used for            │
│ SK_ExtractSubvector are within [0, NumElts), and thus within the BaseVF  │
│ computed from alignTo(NumElts, EltsPerVector). Given EltsPerVector <=    │
│ NumElts and BaseVF >= NumElts (or equal for fixed vectors), the          │
│ assertion (Idx + EltsPerVector) <= BaseVF will hold. It aligns the       │
│ handling of the first and second registers (OffsetReg1 already modulo    │
│ NumElts), avoiding out-of-range subvector extraction cost estimation.\n- │
│ This change is localized to cost estimation and maintains the intended   │
│ semantics of per-register shuffle analysis.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash │
│ was due to an out-of-range subvector extract index produced by           │
│ CheckPerRegistersShuffle. Normalizing the first index to the source      │
│ vector element range fixes the assertion by keeping Idx within valid     │
│ bounds. The fix is minimal, consistent with the existing handling for    │
│ the second index, and should prevent the abort while preserving cost     │
│ modeling correctness for SLP shuffles and extracts."})                   │
